revision.text:
{{short description|The study of ocean chemistry}} '''Chemical oceanography''' is the study of [[ocean chemistry]]: the behavior of the [[chemical element]]s within the [[Earth]]'s [[ocean]]s. The ocean is unique in that it contains - in greater or lesser quantities - nearly every naturally occurring [[chemical element|element]] in the [[periodic table]].
Much of chemical oceanography describes the [[biogeochemical cycle|cycling]] of these elements both within the ocean and with the other [[Earth's spheres|spheres]] of the Earth system (see [[biogeochemical cycle]]). These cycles are usually characterized as quantitative [[flux]]es between constituent [[reservoir (water)|reservoirs]] defined within the ocean system and as [[Residence time (fluid dynamics)|residence time]]s within the ocean. Of particular global and [[climate|climatic]] significance are the cycles of the biologically active elements such as [[carbon cycle|carbon]], [[nitrogen cycle|nitrogen]], and [[phosphorus cycle|phosphorus]] as well as those of some important trace elements such as [[iron]].
Another important area of study in chemical oceanography is the behaviour of [[isotopes]] (see [[isotope geochemistry]]) and how they can be used as tracers of past and present oceanographic and climatic processes. For example, the incidence of <sup>18</sup>O (the heavy isotope of oxygen) can be used as an indicator of polar [[ice sheet]] extent, and [[boron]] isotopes are key indicators of the [[pH]] and [[carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]] content of oceans in the geologic past.
== See also == {{div col|colwidth=30em}} * [[Anoxic event]] - [[Anoxic sea water]] - [[Hypoxia (environmental)]] * [[Climate change]] * [[Dead zone (ecology)]] * [[Global Ocean Data Analysis Project]] * [[Oceanography]] * [[Physical oceanography]] * [[World Ocean Atlas]] {{div col end}}
