'''Redoximorphic features''' ('''RMFs''') consist of color patterns in a [[soil]] that are caused by loss (depletion) or gain (concentration) of pigment compared to the matrix color, formed by [[redox|oxidation/reduction]] of [[iron]] and/or [[manganese]] coupled with their removal, translocation, or accrual; or a soil matrix color controlled by the presence of iron (2+)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schoeneberger,|first=P.J.|last2=Wysocki|first2=D.A.|last3=Benham|first3=E.C.|last4=Soil Survey Staff|date=2012|title=Field book for describing and sampling soils, Version 3.0|url=|journal=Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> The composition and responsible formation processes for a [[soil color]] or color pattern must be known or inferred before it can be described as an RMF.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=H.V. Cabadas-Báez, S. Sedov, S. Jiménez-Álvarez, D. Leonard, B. Lailson-Tinoco, R. García-Moll, I. Ancona-Aragón, L. Hernández.,|first=|date=2017|title=Soils as a Source of Raw Materials for Ancient Ceramic production in the Maya region of Mexico: Micromorphological insight|url=http://boletinsgm.igeolcu.unam.mx/bsgm/vols/epoca04/7001/%282%29Cabadas.pdf|journal=Boletín de la Sociedad Geológica Mexicana|volume=70|pages=21-48|via=}}</ref>
